1. Creational Patterns (The Mechanics of Object Creation)
These patterns provide solutions to instantiate classes in a way that decouples your code from the concrete implementation.

Singleton:
  Description: It restricts a class to a single instance and provides a global access point to that instance.
  Why we prefer it: Some objects should only ever have one instance—like a Configuration Manager or a Database Connection Pool.
                    Creating multiple instances would waste memory and cause synchronization issues.
  Pros: Guaranteed single instance; lazy initialization (created only when needed).
  Cons: Hard to unit test because it introduces global state; can hide dependencies.
  Real Life Usage: The Clipboard on your computer. 
                    No matter how many apps you use, there is only one shared clipboard.
  Java Implementation:
        public class Database {
            private static Database instance;
            private Database() {} // Private to prevent "new"
            public static synchronized Database getInstance() {
                if (instance == null) instance = new Database();
                return instance;
            }
        }
Factory Method:
    Description: It defines an interface for creating an object but lets subclasses decide which class to instantiate.
    Why we prefer it: It promotes Loose Coupling. 
                    The client code doesn't need to know the name of the specific class it is creating; it only knows the interface.
    Pros: Follows the Open/Closed Principle (you can add new types without breaking old code).
    Cons: The code becomes more complex because you need to create many subclasses.
    Real Life Usage: A Logistics Company. 
                    The "App" asks for a "Transport." 
                    If it's a sea route, the factory returns a "Ship"; if it's land, it returns a "Truck."
    Java Implementation:
          interface Animal { void speak(); }
          class Dog implements Animal { public void speak() { System.out.println("Woof"); } }
          class AnimalFactory {
              public Animal createAnimal(String type) {
                  if(type.equals("DOG")) return new Dog();
                  return null;
              }
          }

Abstract Factory:
    Description: A "Factory of Factories." It groups related objects together without specifying their concrete classes.
    Why we prefer it: When you have a "family" of products (e.g., Mac Buttons and Mac Checkboxes) that must be used together to maintain a consistent look.
    Pros: Ensures products from the same factory are compatible.
    Cons: Very difficult to add new product types because you have to change the interface and all factories.
    Real Life Usage: Furniture Styles. A "Modern" factory creates modern chairs and modern sofas. 
                    You wouldn't want a Victorian chair mixed with a Modern sofa.
    Java Implementation:
        interface Chair {}
        interface Table {}
        interface FurnitureFactory { Chair createChair(); Table createTable(); }
        // Implementations for VictorianFactory, ModernFactory, etc.

Builder:
    Description: Separates the construction of a complex object from its representation.
    Why we prefer it: To avoid "Telescoping Constructors" (having a constructor with 15 parameters). 
                    It makes the code readable and allows for immutable objects.
    Pros: Gives fine control over the construction process.
    Cons: Requires creating a separate Builder class for each product.
    Real Life Usage: Ordering a Subway Sandwich. You specify the bread, then the meat, then the sauce. Only at the end is the sandwich "built."
    Java Implementation:
            public class Pizza {
                private String toppings;
                public static class Builder {
                    private Pizza p = new Pizza();
                    public Builder addToppings(String t) { p.toppings = t; return this; }
                    public Pizza build() { return p; }
                }
            }
Prototype
      Description: Creates new objects by cloning an existing "prototype" instance.
      Why we prefer it: Sometimes creating an object from scratch is expensive (e.g., it involves a heavy DB query). 
                        Cloning an existing object is much faster.
      Pros: Reduces initialization overhead.
      Cons: Cloning objects with complex circular references is a nightmare.
      Real Life Usage: Cell Mitosis. A cell doesn't get "constructed" from parts; it clones its existing structure.
      Java Implementation:
            abstract class Shape implements Cloneable {
                public Object clone() { return super.clone(); }
            }

2. Structural Patterns (The Composition of Classes):
  These patterns explain how to assemble objects and classes into larger structures.

Adapter
    Description: Allows incompatible interfaces to work together.
    Why we prefer it: To make legacy code work with a modern system without rewriting the legacy logic.
    Pros: Reusability of existing code.
    Cons: Increases complexity by adding extra "wrapper" classes.
    Real Life Usage: A Travel Power Adapter. It bridges the gap between your American plug and a European socket.
    
    Java Implementation:
        class LegacyJSON { String getJSON() { return "{}"; } }
        interface ModernXML { String getXML(); }
        class JsonToXmlAdapter implements ModernXML {
            private LegacyJSON legacy;
            public String getXML() { return convert(legacy.getJSON()); }
        }

Decorator
    Description: Dynamically adds new functionality to an object without changing its structure.
    Why we prefer it: It's more flexible than inheritance. You can "stack" behaviors at runtime.
    Pros: Can add/remove responsibilities at runtime.
    Cons: It's hard to remove a specific "layer" from the middle of the stack.
    Real Life Usage: Coffee. You have a base coffee, then you "decorate" it with Milk, then with Sugar, then with Caramel.
    Java Implementation:
          interface Coffee { double cost(); }
          class MilkDecorator implements Coffee {
              private Coffee c;
              public MilkDecorator(Coffee c) { this.c = c; }
              public double cost() { return c.cost() + 0.5; }
          }

Facade
      Description: Provides a simplified interface to a complex set of classes (a library or subsystem).
      Why we prefer it: To reduce dependencies. The client only needs to know one simple method instead of 20 complex ones.
      Pros: Makes a library easy to use.
      Cons: The Facade can become a "God Object" tied to everything.
      Real Life Usage: Home Theater. One "Watch Movie" button that turns on the TV, dims the lights, and starts the DVD player.
      Java Implementation:
          class HomeTheaterFacade {
              public void watchMovie() { amp.on(); tv.on(); lights.dim(); }
          }
Proxy
    Description: A placeholder for another object to control access to it.
    Why we prefer it: For Lazy Loading (loading a 100MB image only when viewed) or Security (checking permissions).
    Pros: Controls access; improves performance through caching.
    Cons: Can delay the response if the proxy logic is heavy.
    Real Life Usage: A Credit Card. It is a proxy for your bank account; it controls access to your actual cash.
    Java Implementation:
          class ImageProxy implements Image {
              private RealImage real;
              public void display() { if(real == null) real = new RealImage(); real.display(); }
          }

Composite
    Description: Treats individual objects and compositions (groups) of objects the same way.
    Why we prefer it: It allows you to build tree-like structures (folders/files).
    Pros: Simplifies the client code—it doesn't care if it's talking to one item or a thousand.
    Cons: Hard to restrict what goes into the composite.
    Real Life Usage: Organization Hierarchy. A CEO, a Manager, and a Junior Developer are all "Employees," but a Manager is a composite of other employees.
    Java Implementation:
        interface Employee { void showDetails(); }
        class Manager implements Employee {
            List<Employee> subordinates = new ArrayList<>();
            public void showDetails() { for(Employee e : subordinates) e.showDetails(); }
        }

Flyweight
    Description: Shares objects to support large numbers of small objects efficiently.
    Why we prefer it: To save Memory. Instead of creating 1,000 "Tree" objects, you share the "TreeType" data and only store unique positions.
    Pros: Massive memory savings.
    Cons: Higher CPU usage due to lookup logic.
    Real Life Usage: Word Processors. Instead of every 'A' having its own font data, the letter 'A' is shared, and only its position on the page changes.
    Java Implementation:
        class CharacterFactory {
            private Map<Character, CharObj> cache = new HashMap<>();
            public CharObj getChar(char c) { return cache.computeIfAbsent(c, CharObj::new); }
        }
Bridge
    Description: Decouples an abstraction from its implementation so the two can vary independently.
    Why we prefer it: If you have 2 types of remotes and 2 types of TVs, Bridge stops you from needing 4 separate classes (Remote1TV1, Remote1TV2, etc.).
    Pros: Avoids "class explosion."
    Cons: Increases complexity significantly.
    Real Life Usage: Switch and Light. The switch (abstraction) can work with a bulb, a fan, or a motor (implementations).
    Java Implementation:
          abstract class Remote { protected Device device; }
          class TV implements Device { public void on() { ... } }


3. Behavioral Patterns (Object Communication)
    These patterns handle how objects talk to each other and how they delegate tasks.

Observer
    Description: A "Subscriber" model where objects are notified of any state changes in another object.
    Why we prefer it: To create real-time systems where objects stay in sync without being tightly coupled.
    Pros: Cleanly separates the subject from its observers.
    Cons: If you forget to "unsubscribe," it causes memory leaks.
    Real Life Usage: YouTube. When a creator uploads, all "Subscribers" get a notification.
    Java Implementation:
          class NewsChannel {
              private List<Observer> observers = new ArrayList<>();
              public void notify(String news) { for(Observer o : observers) o.update(news); }
          }

Strategy
    Description: Defines a family of algorithms and makes them interchangeable at runtime.
    Why we prefer it: To get rid of giant if-else or switch blocks.
    Pros: Switch logic at runtime.
    Cons: The client must know which strategy to choose.
    Real Life Usage: Google Maps. You choose a "Strategy" for your route: Walk, Drive, or Bike.
    Java Implementation:
        interface RouteStrategy { void buildRoute(); }
        class DriveStrategy implements RouteStrategy { public void buildRoute() { ... } }

Command
    Description: Turns a request into a stand-alone object.
    Why we prefer it: This allows you to queue requests, log them, or Undo them.
    Pros: Decouples the object that invokes the command from the one that performs it.
    Cons: You end up with a huge number of small classes.
    Real Life Usage: Restaurant Orders. The waiter writes your order on a slip. That slip is the "Command" that can be moved, queued, or cancelled.
    Java Implementation:
          interface Command { void execute(); }
          class LightOnCommand implements Command { public void execute() { light.on(); } }

State
    Description: Allows an object to change its behavior when its internal state changes.
    Why we prefer it: To manage state-heavy logic without 100 nested if statements.
    Pros: Makes state transitions explicit and clean.
    Cons: Overkill if the machine only has 2 states.
    Real Life Usage: Vending Machine. If state is "No Money," the button does nothing. If state is "Has Money," the button gives a soda.
    Java Implementation:
          class Machine {
              private State currentState;
              public void setStatus(State s) { this.currentState = s; }
          }

Chain of Responsibility
    Description: Passes a request along a chain of handlers. Each handler decides to either process it or pass it to the next.
    Why we prefer it: To avoid coupling the sender to a specific receiver.
    Pros: You can add/remove handlers easily.
    Cons: The request might reach the end of the chain without being handled.
    Real Life Usage: Customer Support. L1 support tries to fix it; if they can't, they pass it to L2; then to L3.
    Java Implementation:
        abstract class Logger {
            protected Logger next;
            public void log(String msg) { if(next != null) next.log(msg); }
        }

Iterator
    Description: Provides a way to access elements of a collection sequentially without exposing the underlying structure.
    Why we prefer it: It allows you to traverse a List, a Set, or a Tree using the same next() syntax.
    Pros: Clean code; supports multiple simultaneous traversals.
    Cons: Sometimes slower than a direct for loop.
    Real Life Usage: TV Channels. You don't care if the channels are via Satellite or Cable; you just press "Next" to see the next one.
    Java Implementation:
        Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
        while(it.hasNext()) { String s = it.next(); }

Mediator
    Description: Restricts direct communication between objects and forces them to collaborate only via a mediator object.
    Why we prefer it: It stops the "M:N" dependency problem where every class depends on every other class.
    Pros: Reduces chaotic dependencies.
    Cons: The Mediator itself can become a "Big Ball of Mud."
    Real Life Usage: Air Traffic Control. Pilots don't talk to each other; they only talk to the Tower (The Mediator).
    Java Implementation:
        class Tower {
            public void notify(Plane p, String msg) { ... }
        }

Memento
    Description: Captures and restores an object's internal state without violating encapsulation.
    Why we prefer it: For implementing Checkpoints or "Undo" functionality.
    Pros: You can restore an object to a previous state easily.
    Cons: Storing many "Mementos" consumes a lot of RAM.
    Real Life Usage: Video Game Save Points. You save your state (Memento) and can return to it if you die.
    Java Implementation:
        class EditorMemento { private final String content; ... }


Visitor
    Description: Adds new operations to existing object structures without modifying them.
    Why we prefer it: When you want to perform operations across a whole group of different objects (e.g., Export to JSON, Calculate Taxes).
    Pros: Keeps unrelated logic out of the data classes.
    Cons: If the object structure changes, you have to update every Visitor.
    Real Life Usage: Tax Inspector. They visit your house, your office, and your shop to calculate your tax. They aren't "part" of those buildings.
    Java Implementation:
        interface Visitor { void visit(Book b); void visit(Fruit f); }

Template Method
    Description: Defines the skeleton of an algorithm in a method, deferring some steps to subclasses.
    Why we prefer it: To prevent code duplication. The "Process" is fixed, but the "Steps" can vary.
    Pros: Excellent for code reuse in frameworks.
    Cons: You are limited by the skeleton provided by the parent class.
    Real Life Usage: Building a House. The foundation, walls, and roof are always done in order, but the materials (subclass) can change.
    Java Implementation:
        abstract class Game {
            final void play() { init(); start(); end(); } // Template
            abstract void init();
        }

Interpreter
    Description: Used to define a grammatical representation for a language and an interpreter to deal with this grammar.
    Why we prefer it: For building simple scripting engines or math equation solvers.
    Pros: Easy to change the grammar.
    Cons: Very complex to maintain as the "language" grows.
    Real Life Usage: Roman Numeral Converters. The system interprets 'X', 'V', 'I' into numbers.
    Java Implementation:
        interface Expression { boolean interpret(String context); }

Category      Pattern Type      Key Takeaway
Creational    Creation          Stop using new everywhere; use factories/builders.
Structural    Assembly          Use wrappers (Adapter/Decorator) to connect or expand classes.
Behavioral    Interaction        Use Observers/Strategies to handle complex logic and talk.
  
